    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1066606089" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1066606089" />
    <a title="Kevin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/35434974-kevin"><img alt="Kevin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1607981917p2/35434974.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1066606089?book_show_action=true">Jun 17, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kevin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kevin" href="/user/show/35434974-kevin">Kevin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/35434974-kevin?shelf=z-questionable-reformist">z-questionable-reformist</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/35434974-kevin?shelf=z-propaganda-liberalism">z-propaganda-liberalism</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1066606089" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5515150871415884371">The Maze of Liberal Interventionism...<br/><br/><b>Preamble</b>:<br/>--Note: June 17, 2020, Canada lost its bid for a non-permanent seat on the UN Security Council. This review provides hints to why...<br/>--Looking back, this was one of the first nonfiction I read after my apolitical university years. Given my apolitical Western education, I was a default centrist, in the sense that I inherited the liberal centrist worldview (i.e. bias towards rich, &quot;free&quot;, &quot;peaceful&quot;, &quot;developed&quot; countries, thus missing the structures o</span>
  <span id="freeText5515150871415884371" style="display:none">The Maze of Liberal Interventionism...<br /><br /><b>Preamble</b>:<br />--Note: June 17, 2020, Canada lost its bid for a non-permanent seat on the UN Security Council. This review provides hints to why...<br />--Looking back, this was one of the first nonfiction I read after my apolitical university years. Given my apolitical Western education, I was a default centrist, in the sense that I inherited the liberal centrist worldview (i.e. bias towards rich, "free", "peaceful", "developed" countries, thus missing the structures of history, power relations and capitalism's global division of labor). <br />--Having grown up in Canada, this liberal worldview came more in the form of liberal democratic <b>"peacekeeping"</b> against "dictators"/"regimes" rather than the blatant freedom-bombs of American exceptionalism. <br />--US's abominable <b>"War on Terror"</b> helped open up the contradiction with this worldview. It was the tip of the iceberg to modern capitalist empire and its roots in liberalism (i.e. those who "developed" the land deserve to own it, never mind the fact that the laboring slaves and indentured/wage laborers owned scraps); the zealot lapdog stenographers of the corporate "free press" have now tactfully backtracked from the "War on Terror" and have evolved towards "Great-Power competition" (hence Russiagate and China trade war). <br /><br /><b>The Missing/Questionable</b>:<br />--Well, this book did little to clarify this contradiction. Let us not get lost in individual character analysis of the author, a Canadian soldier sent to lead the United Nations Assistance Mission for Rwanda (UNAMIR). The pressing questions are structural: <b>historical context + power relations</b> behind "peacekeeping". <br />--On the structural level, liberal interventionism has grim roots in historical colonialism and the power relations of imperialism (i.e. preserving capitalism's global division of labor). Foot soldiers may not be the best to tell the full story, although it has to be said that Dallaire became a politician for the Canadian Liberal Party whereas the famous US Major General <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/115545.Smedley_D__Butler" title="Smedley D. Butler" rel="nofollow noopener">Smedley D. Butler</a> became an anti-war activist and spoke out against his career as a "<b>gangster of capitalism"</b>: <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/24013955.War_is_a_Racket_The_Antiwar_Classic_by_America_s_Most_Decorated_Soldier" title="War is a Racket The Antiwar Classic by America's Most Decorated Soldier by Smedley D. Butler" rel="nofollow noopener">War is a Racket: The Antiwar Classic by America's Most Decorated Soldier</a><br />--Meanwhile, Dallaire supported <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/50189.Michael_Ignatieff" title="Michael Ignatieff" rel="nofollow noopener">Michael Ignatieff</a> in his failed bid to become Canada's Prime Minister. Ignatieff popularized militarized peacekeeping in the form of "<b>Responsibility to Protect</b>" (R2P). Even more repulsive is to have the war-mongering <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/13271.Samantha_Power" title="Samantha Power" rel="nofollow noopener">Samantha Power</a> provide the book's foreword. It becomes much easier to see pass the "good intentions" veneer of these two-faced politicians beholden to preserving global capitalism's wealth and poverty when you review:<br /><br />--The History of Liberalism's violence and the struggles against it:<br />a) Beyond liberal imperialist propaganda: <br />-<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/10707.Vijay_Prashad" title="Vijay Prashad" rel="nofollow noopener">Vijay Prashad</a> on imperialism's "<b>ideological censorship</b>": <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://youtu.be/6jKcsHv3c74">https://youtu.be/6jKcsHv3c74</a><br />-<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/848628.Necessary_Illusions_Thought_Control_in_Democratic_Societies" title="Necessary Illusions Thought Control in Democratic Societies by Noam Chomsky" rel="nofollow noopener">Necessary Illusions: Thought Control in Democratic Societies</a><br />b) Crucially, alternatives proposed in <b>decolonization</b> and <b>socialism</b> to challenge liberal imperialism and the "need" for liberal interventions: <br />-Decolonization struggles (even reaching state laws and global diplomacy) towards internationalist nationalism, anti-racist secular state, global disarmament, global economic justice, expanded universal human rights, etc.: <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17609.The_Darker_Nations_A_People_s_History_of_the_Third_World" title="The Darker Nations A People's History of the Third World by Vijay Prashad" rel="nofollow noopener">The Darker Nations: A People's History of the Third World</a><br />-Decolonization's domestic land reforms and social programs (public healthcare, literacy, participatory democracy, etc.): <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLSQhQoKnYhTXceMPfa4MYyJjnm5ScFIZ_">https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list...</a><br />c) Details on intervention:<br />-Prashad on on the "foreign policy of the 1%": <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://youtu.be/DiHtfeof15s?t=52">https://youtu.be/DiHtfeof15s?t=52</a><br />-Prashad on "Responsibility to Protect (R2P)": <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://youtu.be/1MiYazFZYpI?t=494">https://youtu.be/1MiYazFZYpI?t=494</a><br />-<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/433661.Yves_Engler" title="Yves Engler" rel="nofollow noopener">Yves Engler</a> has a lot of specifics on Canadian foreign policy's violence, including: <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/6884153.The_Black_Book_of_Canadian_Foreign_Policy" title="The Black Book of Canadian Foreign Policy by Yves Engler" rel="nofollow noopener">The Black Book of Canadian Foreign Policy</a> and <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/22012922.Lester_Pearson_s_Peacekeeping___The_Truth_May_Hurt" title="Lester Pearson's Peacekeeping - The Truth May Hurt by Yves Engler" rel="nofollow noopener">Lester Pearson's Peacekeeping - The Truth May Hurt</a> <br />d) History of US interventionism:<br />-<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/78130.Killing_Hope_U_S__Military_and_C_I_A__Interventions_Since_World_War_II" title="Killing Hope U.S. Military and C.I.A. Interventions Since World War II by William Blum" rel="nofollow noopener">Killing Hope: U.S. Military and C.I.A. Interventions Since World War II</a><br />-<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/53054943.The_Jakarta_Method_Washington_s_Anticommunist_Crusade_and_the_Mass_Murder_Program_that_Shaped_Our_World" title="The Jakarta Method Washington's Anticommunist Crusade and the Mass Murder Program that Shaped Our World by Vincent Bevins" rel="nofollow noopener">The Jakarta Method: Washington's Anticommunist Crusade and the Mass Murder Program that Shaped Our World</a><br />-<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/44771267.The_Management_of_Savagery_How_America_s_National_Security_State_Fueled_the_Rise_of_Al_Qaeda__ISIS__and_Donald_Trump" title="The Management of Savagery How America's National Security State Fueled the Rise of Al Qaeda, ISIS, and Donald Trump by Max Blumenthal" rel="nofollow noopener">The Management of Savagery: How America's National Security State Fueled the Rise of Al Qaeda, ISIS, and Donald Trump</a><br />e) Older/longer histories:<br />-<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7859.Late_Victorian_Holocausts_El_Ni_o_Famines_and_the_Making_of_the_Third_World" title="Late Victorian Holocausts El Ni√±o Famines and the Making of the Third World by Mike Davis" rel="nofollow noopener">Late Victorian Holocausts: El Ni√±o Famines and the Making of the Third World</a><br />-<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2690635.Perilous_Passage_Mankind_and_the_Global_Ascendancy_of_Capital" title="Perilous Passage Mankind and the Global Ascendancy of Capital by Amiya Kumar Bagchi" rel="nofollow noopener">Perilous Passage: Mankind and the Global Ascendancy of Capital</a><br /><br />...other related works I have not read but look extremely relevant:<br />-<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/947529.Aiding_Violence_The_Development_Enterprise_In_Rwanda" title="Aiding Violence The Development Enterprise In Rwanda by Peter Uvin" rel="nofollow noopener">Aiding Violence: The Development Enterprise In Rwanda</a><br />-<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7868957.The_Politics_of_Genocide" title="The Politics of Genocide by Edward S. Herman" rel="nofollow noopener">The Politics of Genocide</a> (author <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/7985.Edward_S__Herman" title="Edward S. Herman" rel="nofollow noopener">Edward S. Herman</a> was the lead author for <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/12617.Manufacturing_Consent_The_Political_Economy_of_the_Mass_Media" title="Manufacturing Consent The Political Economy of the Mass Media by Edward S. Herman" rel="nofollow noopener">Manufacturing Consent: The Political Economy of the Mass Media</a>, which of course is well-known for readers of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/2476.Noam_Chomsky" title="Noam Chomsky" rel="nofollow noopener">Noam Chomsky</a>)</span>
  <a data-text-id="5515150871415884371" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
