    <a title="Margarita" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3082367-margarita"><img alt="Margarita" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1540081876p2/3082367.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1479137978?book_show_action=true">Sep 10, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Margarita" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Margarita" href="/user/show/3082367-margarita">Margarita</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3082367-margarita?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1479137978" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10485860416144632968">This is a compelling account of what Lieutenant General Dallaire‚Äôs experiences as a UN Force Commander in Rwanda were like in the early nineties. His account is partly self-defence and partly placing blame. All of it is a detailed play-by-play of his perspective on the numerous barriers he faced in seeing through his mission. To be clear, it is not a balanced perspective nor can it be expected to be. You will be left feeling like humanity has failed and perhaps it has. So, with that said, it‚Äôs c</span>
  <span id="freeText10485860416144632968" style="display:none">This is a compelling account of what Lieutenant General Dallaire‚Äôs experiences as a UN Force Commander in Rwanda were like in the early nineties. His account is partly self-defence and partly placing blame. All of it is a detailed play-by-play of his perspective on the numerous barriers he faced in seeing through his mission. To be clear, it is not a balanced perspective nor can it be expected to be. You will be left feeling like humanity has failed and perhaps it has. So, with that said, it‚Äôs critical that this account be read with an open-mind. Here you are given one very pointed perspective on a situation that is ridiculously complex. I‚Äôm not arguing against the merits of his perspective; I‚Äôm simply articulating that it is but one perspective. This book doesn‚Äôt provide adequate context on the complexities that existed in Rwanda prior to the Arusha Peace Agreement. To gain a greater understanding of Rwanda during the genocide in the early nineties, additional reading is absolutely essential. This account though by Lieutenant General Dallaire is an excellent place to start.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10485860416144632968" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
